If you add a new feature to the decompiler you will want an easy way to test it - and re-test it, every time you make
another change to the decompiler.

The Ghidra developers made that easy, with no need to start up a new Ghidra GUI instance.

Suppose you want to test new decompiler code that transforms Pcode sequences into more human-readable decompiler output.
The decompiler source includes the target `testfunction` which runs all of the data tests in
`Ghidra/Features/Decompiler/src/decompile/datatests`.  The `heapstring.xml` test sets the architecture as `x86:LE:64:default:gcc`,
loads a `binaryimage` set of `bytechunks` holding raw binary, then defines some `structs` and `functions`.  This test
then provides a script to exercise the decompiler and a set of `stringmatch` assertions that `decompile` and `print C` commands
will generate specific calls to `builtin_strncpy` and `builtin_memcpy`.

This test exercises two transformation Rules defined in `constseq.hh` and `constseq.cc`.  These rules search for multibyte
loads and stores that can be condensed into single invocations of `builtin_strncpy` and `builtin_memcpy`.  The x86_64 multibyte load and
store instructions can be more than a little confusing, so this transformation is well worthwhile.

If we don't want to run *all* of the datatests within the `testfunction` test harness, we can translate the `heapstring.xml` test into
a standalone decompiler test:

First slice the binary data and core type information out of `heapstring.xml` into test/heapstring_save.xml.  That will look like:
```xml
<xml_savefile name="main" target="default" adjustvma="0">
    <binaryimage arch="x86:LE:64:default:gcc">
        <bytechunk space="ram" offset="0x100000" readonly="true">
            f30f1efa48ba4d6573736167653a488b
            07488910c6400820c3
    </bytechunk>
    </binaryimage>
    <coretypes>
        <void />
        <type name="int" size="4" metatype="int" id="-9223370945157383201" />
        <type name="char" size="1" metatype="int" char="true" id="-9223091865880322087" />
    </coretypes>
</xml_savefile>
```

Next select the decompiler commands out of `heapstring.xml` into `test/heapstring.ghidra`:

```text
restore test/heapstring_save.xml
map function 0x100000 fillin
option readonly on
parse line struct mystring { char *val; int len; };
parse line extern void fillin(mystring *ptr);
load function fillin
decompile
print raw
print C
```

Regenerate the raw binary `heapstring.bin` by echoing "f30f1efa48ba4d6573736167653a488b07488910c6400820c3" through `xxd -r -p`.
Import that into Ghidra so we know what we are starting with.

Ghidra's listing window shows:

```text

                    FUN_00000000:
00000000 f3 0f 1e fa     ENDBR64
00000004 48 ba 4d        MOV     RDX,0x3a6567617373654d
         65 73 73 
         61 67 65 3a
0000000e 48 8b 07        MOV     RAX,qword ptr [ptr->val]
00000011 48 89 10        MOV     qword ptr [RAX],RDX
00000014 c6 40 08 20     MOV     byte ptr [RAX + 0x8],0x20
00000018 c3              RET
```

The decompiler window is much easier to understand, after setting the function signature correctly:

```c
void FUN_00000000(mystring *ptr)
{
  builtin_strncpy(ptr->val,"Message: ",9);
  return;
}
```

Now run the standalone data test:

```console
$  SLEIGHHOME=/opt/ghidra_12.1_DEV/  /opt/ghidra_12.1_DEV/Ghidra/Features/Decompiler/os/linux_x86_64/decompile_datatest < test/heapstring.ghidra
